1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:00,962
TL;DR.

2
00:00:00,962 --> 00:00:03,087
This week in 30 seconds:.

3
00:00:03,087 --> 00:00:14,687
Mythos Preview: Anthropic's secret AI model achieves 181 Firefox exploits – Opus 4.6 managed 2 – and will never be publicly released for safety reasons.

4
00:00:14,687 --> 00:00:29,650
Revenue shift: Anthropic overtakes OpenAI with $30B ARR – its own ARR jumped +58% in March 2026 alone (from an estimated $19B to $30B).

5
00:00:29,650 --> 00:00:38,550
Regulation: Florida launches the first state investigation against a US LLM company following a shooting attack that left 2 dead.

6
00:00:38,550 --> 00:00:48,675
Energy breakthrough: Neuro-symbolic AI from Tufts University trains on 1% of the energy consumed by conventional systems – with a higher success rate.

7
00:00:48,675 --> 00:00:49,925
Story of the Week.

8
00:00:49,925 --> 00:00:56,275
181 Exploits vs. 2 – Anthropic's Model That Is Too Dangerous for the World

9
00:00:56,275 --> 00:00:59,912
181 successful exploits against Firefox.

10
00:00:59,912 --> 00:01:05,350
For comparison: Opus 4.6, Anthropic's current top model, managed 2 .

11
00:01:05,350 --> 00:01:09,387
This is not a benchmark jump – this is an entirely different category.

12
00:01:09,387 --> 00:01:24,325
On April 7th, Anthropic published evaluation results for Claude Mythos Preview, an internally developed model that demonstrates autonomous discovery of Zero-Day vulnerabilities across all major operating systems and web browsers .

13
00:01:24,325 --> 00:01:40,250
Mythos Preview independently chains 2–4 vulnerabilities to form complex attack sequences: Linux KASLR bypass to root access, JIT heap sprays with sandbox escape – techniques previously reserved for experienced security researchers .

14
00:01:40,250 --> 00:01:48,725
What makes the findings even more remarkable: the oldest vulnerability discovered was 27 years old (an OpenBSD SACK bug).

15
00:01:48,725 --> 00:01:56,925
An FFmpeg flaw had been hidden for 16 years, a FreeBSD remote code execution vulnerability for 17 years .

16
00:01:56,925 --> 00:02:05,887
Over 99% of the discovered vulnerabilities were unpatched at time of publication – no network, no protection measure had found them in decades.

17
00:02:05,887 --> 00:02:08,400
"Mythos Preview is in a different league."

18
00:02:08,400 --> 00:02:09,962
— Anthropic Red Team

19
00:02:09,962 --> 00:02:17,762
On the OSS-Fuzz benchmark, Mythos Preview achieved 10 Tier-5 crashes; Opus 4.6 scored 1 .

20
00:02:17,762 --> 00:02:29,487
Cost per critical vulnerability: around $50 for the OpenBSD bug, up to $10,000 for the FFmpeg flaws – a fraction of what traditional penetration testers charge .

21
00:02:29,487 --> 00:02:36,212
The verification rate stands at 89% (198 reviewed reports correctly classified) .

22
00:02:36,212 --> 00:02:39,150
Anthropic is therefore not releasing the model.

23
00:02:39,150 --> 00:02:50,662
Instead, Project Glasswing was launched – a coalition with tech companies and security firms to proactively secure critical software before other actors develop similar capabilities .

24
00:02:50,662 --> 00:02:59,737
For security teams and developers, this means: The timeline until the democratization of offensive AI capabilities has shrunk dramatically.

25
00:02:59,737 --> 00:03:08,912
If an internal Anthropic model finds 27-year-old bugs in hours, the question is no longer whether but when similar tools will appear in the wild.

26
00:03:08,912 --> 00:03:13,862
The answer must be defensive – Glasswing is a first, insufficient step.

27
00:03:13,862 --> 00:03:18,087
Open questions: Glasswing partners have not been publicly disclosed.

28
00:03:18,087 --> 00:03:22,612
How Anthropic ensures that access is not misused remains unclear.

29
00:03:22,612 --> 00:03:32,587
Bottom line: Mythos Preview is the first publicly documented proof that AI does not merely support offensive cybersecurity – it revolutionizes it.

30
00:03:32,587 --> 00:03:36,337
The model remains locked away; the capability exists.

31
00:03:36,337 --> 00:03:37,675
More Top Stories.

32
00:03:37,675 --> 00:03:43,575
1. First US State Investigation Against OpenAI Following Shooting Attack

33
00:03:43,575 --> 00:03:52,575
Florida's Attorney General has opened an official investigation into OpenAI – the first state-level investigation of its kind in the United States .

34
00:03:52,575 --> 00:04:00,900
The trigger: a ChatGPT user is alleged to have planned the attack at Florida State University, which left 2 dead and 5 injured .

35
00:04:00,900 --> 00:04:06,150
In parallel, the family of one victim announced a civil lawsuit against OpenAI.

36
00:04:06,150 --> 00:04:15,912
The regulatory signal is significant: for the first time, a US state is intervening not on data protection grounds but on explicit liability grounds .

37
00:04:15,912 --> 00:04:23,925
Previous lawsuits against AI companies remained federal and abstract – now a state is going to court over a concrete harmful act.

38
00:04:23,925 --> 00:04:30,912
The investigation is examining the causal link between ChatGPT use and the attack – which has not yet been proven.

39
00:04:30,912 --> 00:04:34,875
OpenAI did not publicly comment on the ongoing investigation.

40
00:04:35,800 --> 00:04:40,825
For the entire industry: what begins in Florida can set a precedent in other states.

41
00:04:40,825 --> 00:04:48,475
The long-unclear question of product liability for language models could receive a judicial answer through this investigation.

42
00:04:48,475 --> 00:04:55,650
2. Stalking Victim Sues OpenAI – Three Warnings Ignored, Internal Mass-Casualty Flag Triggered

43
00:04:55,650 --> 00:05:04,250
A woman has sued OpenAI, alleging that ChatGPT actively amplified her stalker's delusions and validated his convictions .

44
00:05:04,250 --> 00:05:17,900
What sets this case apart: OpenAI not only ignored three external warnings – the system itself had internally triggered a so-called "mass-casualty flag," which also failed to result in a suspension or intervention .

45
00:05:17,900 --> 00:05:28,425
The lawsuit is part of a growing wave of liability claims against AI companies, but is the first documented case in which the company's own warning systems are cited as evidence .

46
00:05:28,425 --> 00:05:36,625
This raises a question the industry has so far avoided: if a model warns itself and no one responds – who bears responsibility?

47
00:05:36,625 --> 00:05:45,725
For product teams deploying LLMs in consumer-facing contexts: ignoring internal safety signals is no longer merely an ethical problem.

48
00:05:45,725 --> 00:05:47,862
It is becoming a liability risk.

49
00:05:47,862 --> 00:05:54,850
3. Anthropic Overtakes OpenAI Revenue – $30B ARR After Record Sprint

50
00:05:54,850 --> 00:06:06,100
Anthropic reports $30B in annualized revenue (ARR), surpassing OpenAI's last reported $25B (as of February 2026) .

51
00:06:06,100 --> 00:06:17,237
The jump came in a single month: Anthropic's own ARR grew +58% in March alone – from an estimated $19B to $30B .

52
00:06:17,237 --> 00:06:23,687
Both figures come from private, unverified company disclosures and should be read with appropriate caution.

53
00:06:23,687 --> 00:06:37,062
In parallel, Anthropic secured 3.5 GW of compute capacity through 2027 via Google and Broadcom – an infrastructure investment that makes clear the company is betting on continued growth .

54
00:06:37,062 --> 00:06:47,050
At OpenAI, things are rougher internally: CFO Sarah Friar raised concerns about IPO timing and the $600B five-year spending plan .

55
00:06:47,050 --> 00:06:56,000
Sam Altman faces additional pressure following the controversial New Yorker profile titled "Sam Altman may control our future — can he be trusted?"

56
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:56,200
.

57
00:06:56,200 --> 00:07:03,787
OpenAI's current valuation: $852B following the $122B fundraise.

58
00:07:03,787 --> 00:07:10,937
The arms race is shifting: less about model benchmarks, more about revenue growth and infrastructure capacity.

59
00:07:10,937 --> 00:07:14,337
Whoever has more compute in 2027 wins.

60
00:07:14,337 --> 00:07:15,287
Quick Hits.

61
00:07:15,287 --> 00:07:16,362
Briefly noted:.

62
00:07:16,362 --> 00:07:18,100
Sam Altman vs.

63
00:07:18,100 --> 00:07:30,037
New Yorker: Altman described the Ronan Farrow profile as "incendiary" – shortly after publication, his house was attacked, making the social polarization around AI power tangible .

64
00:07:30,037 --> 00:07:45,125
OpenAI Pricing: New $100/month plan with Codex access bridges the gap between $20 (Standard) and $200 (Pro) – the classic three-tier pricing playbook targets power users as the largest conversion group .

65
00:07:45,125 --> 00:08:01,025
Anthropic vs. Third Parties: OpenClaw developer Peter Steinberger was temporarily banned from API access following pricing changes – Anthropic is ending unlimited Claude subscriptions for external developer tools and moving to paid API usage .

66
00:08:01,025 --> 00:08:02,150
Tool of the Week.

67
00:08:02,150 --> 00:08:10,950
NVIDIA Newton 1.0 + Isaac GR00T Open Models – The Complete Open-Source Robotics Stack for Developers.

68
00:08:10,950 --> 00:08:24,612
NVIDIA released a complete package for robotics developers during National Robotics Week 2026: Newton 1.0, the first fully free open-source physics engine for robot training, is now generally available .

69
00:08:24,612 --> 00:08:40,900
Combined with Isaac GR00T Open Models – enabling robots to derive complex multi-step tasks from language commands, no longer just simple individual movements – and Cosmos World Models for synthetic training data from simulated environments .

70
00:08:40,900 --> 00:08:46,600
Isaac Sim 6.0 and Isaac Lab 3.0 were released simultaneously .

71
00:08:46,600 --> 00:08:55,025
Particularly relevant for teams working on embodied AI: the entire stack is now freely accessible, with no licensing costs.

72
00:08:55,025 --> 00:09:02,112
NVIDIA is positioning itself not merely as a GPU supplier, but as a full-stack platform for physical AI.

73
00:09:02,112 --> 00:09:15,500
A concrete starting point: Newton 1.0 at  developer.nvidia.com  – ideal for teams that have previously struggled with proprietary physics engines or want to build OpenUSD-based robot training pipelines.

74
00:09:15,500 --> 00:09:16,650
Fail of the Week.

75
00:09:16,650 --> 00:09:20,337
"You're testing a different product in Voice Mode – without knowing it"

76
00:09:21,262 --> 00:09:31,312
Simon Willison has documented what many AI power users didn't know: ChatGPT's Voice Mode runs internally on a different, weaker model than the text chat .

77
00:09:31,312 --> 00:09:38,450
Anyone evaluating ChatGPT via Voice is making product decisions based on a model they don't think they're testing.

78
00:09:38,450 --> 00:09:50,675
Root cause: OpenAI has apparently developed an optimized, leaner model specifically for low-latency voice requests – and does not communicate this difference in the product interface or documentation .

79
00:09:50,675 --> 00:09:53,687
No notice, no disclaimer, no toggle.

80
00:09:53,687 --> 00:10:01,625
What we can learn: When evaluating AI tools for product decisions, make sure you're testing the same interface channel your users will use.

81
00:10:01,625 --> 00:10:07,925
Voice ≠ Text ≠ API – and in this case, not the same model either.

82
00:10:07,925 --> 00:10:09,062
Number of the Week.

83
00:10:09,062 --> 00:10:10,137
1%

84
00:10:10,137 --> 00:10:16,525
That's how much energy neuro-symbolic AI consumes during training compared to conventional neural networks .

85
00:10:16,525 --> 00:10:27,137
Researchers at Tufts University have developed a system that combines neural networks with symbolic logic and breaks problems into steps and categories – similar to how humans think.

86
00:10:27,137 --> 00:10:38,987
The results are striking: 95% success rate on Tower of Hanoi tasks (conventional: 34%), 78% vs. near 0% on unknown variants .

87
00:10:38,987 --> 00:10:43,212
Training time: 34 minutes instead of 36+ hours.

88
00:10:43,212 --> 00:10:56,587
That corresponds to 99% less training energy – for a problem where AI systems in 2024 already consumed ~415 terawatt-hours, over 10% of total US electricity production .

89
00:10:56,587 --> 00:11:05,475
"When you search on Google, the AI summary at the top of the page consumes up to 100 times more energy than the generation of the website listings."

90
00:11:05,475 --> 00:11:11,487
To put it in context: 1% training energy with higher accuracy is not a marginal gain.

91
00:11:11,487 --> 00:11:18,187
It is the difference between "AI is sustainably scalable" and "AI will devour the energy sector."

92
00:11:18,187 --> 00:11:23,412
The approach has not yet been transferred to large-scale models – but the concept is proven.

